# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: misra-c
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:misra-c/cert-c-coding-standard] The SEI **CERT Coding Standards** are software coding standards developed by the CERT Coordination Center to improve the safety, reliability, and security of software systems.
[src:misra-c/cert-c-coding-standard] Individual standards are offered for C, C++, Java, Android OS, and Perl.
[src:misra-c/cert-c-coding-standard] Guidelines in the CERT C Secure Coding Standard are cross-referenced with several other standards including Common Weakness Enumeration (CWE) entries and MISRA.
[src:misra-c/coding-conventions] Reducing the cost of software maintenance is the most often cited reason for following coding conventions.
[src:misra-c/coding-conventions] Software peer review frequently involves reading source code.
[src:misra-c/coding-conventions] This type of peer review is primarily a defect detection activity.
[src:misra-c/coding-conventions] By definition, only the original author of a piece of code has read the source file before the code is submitted for review.
[src:misra-c/coding-conventions] Code that is written using consistent guidelines is easier for other reviewers to understand and assimilate, improving the efficacy of the defect detection process.
[src:misra-c/coding-conventions] Even for the original author, consistently coded software eases maintainability.
[src:misra-c/coding-conventions] There is no guarantee that an individual will remember the precise rationale for why a particular piece of code was written in a certain way long after the code was originally written.
[src:misra-c/coding-conventions] Consistent use of whitespace improves readability and reduces the time it takes to understand the software.
[src:misra-c/coding-conventions] Where coding conventions have been specifically designed to produce high-quality code, and have then been formally adopted, they then become coding standards.
[src:misra-c/coding-conventions] Specific styles, irrespective of whether they are commonly adopted, do not automatically produce good quality code.
[src:misra-c/coding-conventions] Complexity is a factor going against security.
[src:misra-c/coding-conventions] The management of complexity includes the following basic principle: minimize the amount of code written during the project development.
[src:misra-c/coding-conventions] This prevents unnecessary work which prevents unnecessary cost, both upfront and downstream.
[src:misra-c/coding-conventions] This is simply because if there is less code, it is less work not only to create the application, but also to maintain it.
[src:misra-c/coding-conventions] Complexity is managed both at the design stage (how the project is architectured) and at the development stage (by having simpler code).
[src:misra-c/coding-conventions] If the coding is kept basic and simple then the complexity will be minimised.
[src:misra-c/coding-conventions] Very often this is keeping the coding as 'physical' as possible - coding in a manner that is very direct and not highly abstract.
[src:misra-c/coding-conventions] This produces optimal code that is easy to read and follow.
[src:misra-c/coding-conventions] Complexity can also be avoided simply by not using complicated tools for simple jobs.
[src:misra-c/coding-conventions] The more complex the code is the more likely it is to be buggy, the more difficult the bugs are to find and the more likely there are to be hidden bugs.
[src:misra-c/coding-conventions] Refactoring refers to a software maintenance activity where source code is modified to improve readability or improve its structure.
[src:misra-c/coding-conventions] Software is often refactored to bring it into conformance with a team's stated coding standards after its initial release.
[src:misra-c/coding-conventions] Any change that does not alter the behavior of the software can be considered refactoring.
[src:misra-c/coding-conventions] Common refactoring activities are changing variable names, renaming methods, moving methods or whole classes and breaking large methods (or functions) into smaller ones.
[src:misra-c/coding-conventions] Agile software development methodologies plan for regular (or even continuous) refactoring making it an integral part of the team software development process.
[src:misra-c/coding-conventions] Coding conventions allow programmers to have simple scripts or programs whose job is to process source code for some purpose other than compiling it into an executable.
[src:misra-c/coding-conventions] It is common practice to count the software size (Source lines of code) to track current project progress or establish a baseline for future project estimates.
[src:misra-c/coding-conventions] Consistent coding standards can, in turn, make the measurements more consistent.
[src:misra-c/coding-conventions] Special tags within source code comments are often used to process documentation, two notable examples are javadoc and doxygen.
[src:misra-c/coding-conventions] The tools specify the use of a set of tags, but their use within a project is determined by convention.
[src:misra-c/coding-conventions] Coding conventions simplify writing new software whose job is to process existing software.
[src:misra-c/coding-conventions] Use of static code analysis has grown consistently since the 1950s.
[src:misra-c/coding-conventions] Some of the growth of this class of development tools stems from increased maturity and sophistication of the practitioners themselves (and the modern focus on safety and security), but also from the nature of the languages themselves.
[src:misra-c/coding-conventions] All software practitioners must grapple with the problem of organizing and managing a large number of sometimes complex instructions.
[src:misra-c/coding-conventions] For all but the smallest software projects, source code (instructions) are partitioned into separate files and frequently among many directories.
[src:misra-c/coding-conventions] It was natural for programmers to collect closely related functions (behaviors) in the same file and to collect related files into directories.
[src:misra-c/coding-conventions] As software development shifted from purely procedural programming (such as found in FORTRAN) towards more object-oriented constructs (such as found in C++), it became the practice to write the code for a single (public) class in a single file (the 'one class per file' convention).
[src:misra-c/coding-conventions] Java has gone one step further - the Java compiler returns an error if it finds more than one public class per file.
[src:misra-c/coding-conventions] A convention in one language may be a requirement in another.
[src:misra-c/coding-conventions] Language conventions also affect individual source files.
[src:misra-c/coding-conventions] Each compiler (or interpreter) used to process source code is unique.
[src:misra-c/coding-conventions] The rules a compiler applies to the source creates implicit standards.
[src:misra-c/coding-conventions] For example, Python code is much more consistently indented than, say Perl, because whitespace (indentation) is actually significant to the interpreter.
[src:misra-c/coding-conventions] Python does not use the brace syntax Perl uses to delimit functions.
[src:misra-c/coding-conventions] Changes in indentation serve as the delimiters.
[src:misra-c/coding-conventions] The reason is that in Tcl, curly braces are not used only to delimit functions as in C or Java.
[src:misra-c/coding-conventions] More generally, curly braces are used to group words together into a single argument.
[src:misra-c/coding-conventions] In Tcl, the *word* **while** takes two arguments, a *condition* and an *action*.
[src:misra-c/coding-conventions] In the example above, **while** is missing its second argument, its *action* (because the Tcl also uses the newline character to delimit the end of a command).
[src:misra-c/coding-conventions] There are a large number of coding conventions; see *Coding Style* for numerous examples and discussion.
[src:misra-c/coding-conventions] Coding standards include the CERT C Coding Standard, MISRA C, High Integrity C++.
[src:misra-c/defensive-programming] Overly defensive programming, however, may safeguard against errors that will never be encountered, thus incurring run-time and maintenance costs.
[src:misra-c/defensive-programming] Secure programming is the subset of defensive programming concerned with computer security.
[src:misra-c/defensive-programming] Security is the concern, not necessarily safety or availability (the software may be allowed to fail in certain ways).
[src:misra-c/defensive-programming] The function will result in undefined behavior when the input is over 1000 characters.
[src:misra-c/defensive-programming] Some programmers may not feel that this is a problem, supposing that no user will enter such a long input.
[src:misra-c/defensive-programming] This particular bug demonstrates a vulnerability which enables buffer overflow exploits.
[src:misra-c/defensive-programming] Offensive programming is a category of defensive programming, with the added emphasis that certain errors should *not* be handled defensively.
[src:misra-c/defensive-programming] In this practice, only errors from outside the program's control are to be handled (such as user input); the software itself, as well as data from within the program's line of defense, are to be trusted in this methodology.
[src:misra-c/defensive-programming] If existing code is tested and known to work, reusing it may reduce the chance of bugs being introduced.
[src:misra-c/defensive-programming] However, reusing code is not *always* good practice.
[src:misra-c/defensive-programming] Reuse of existing code, especially when widely distributed, can allow for exploits to be created that target a wider audience than would otherwise be possible and brings with it all the security and vulnerabilities of the reused code.
[src:misra-c/defensive-programming] When considering using existing source code, a quick review of the modules(sub-sections such as classes or functions) will help eliminate or make the developer aware of any potential vulnerabilities and ensure it is suitable to use in the project.
[src:misra-c/defensive-programming] Before reusing old source code, libraries, APIs, configurations and so forth, it must be considered if the old work is valid for reuse, or if it is likely to be prone to legacy problems.
[src:misra-c/defensive-programming] Legacy problems are problems inherent when old designs are expected to work with today's requirements, especially when the old designs were not developed or tested with those requirements in mind.
[src:misra-c/defensive-programming] Malicious users are likely to invent new kinds of representations of incorrect data.
[src:misra-c/defensive-programming] For example, if a program attempts to reject accessing the file "/etc/passwd", a cracker might pass another variant of this file name, like "/etc/./passwd".
[src:misra-c/defensive-programming] Canonicalization libraries can be employed to avoid bugs due to non-canonical input.
[src:misra-c/defensive-programming] Assume that code constructs that appear to be problem prone (similar to known vulnerabilities, etc.) are bugs and potential security flaws.
[src:misra-c/defensive-programming] The basic rule of thumb is: "I'm not aware of all types of security exploits.
[src:misra-c/defensive-programming] I must protect against those I *do* know of and then I must be proactive!".
[src:misra-c/misra-c] There is also a set of guidelines for MISRA C++ not covered by this article.
[src:misra-c/misra-c] For the first two editions of MISRA-C (1998 and 2004) all Guidelines were considered as Rules.
[src:misra-c/misra-c] With the publication of MISRA C:2012 a new category of Guideline was introduced - the *Directive* whose compliance is more open to interpretation, or relates to process or procedural matters.
[src:misra-c/misra-c] Although originally specifically targeted at the automotive industry, MISRA C has evolved as a widely accepted model for best practices by leading developers in sectors including automotive, aerospace, telecom, medical devices, defense, railway, and others.
[src:misra-c/misra-c] When a new software project is started, the latest MISRA standard should be used.
[src:misra-c/misra-c] Previous standards are still available for use with legacy software projects that need to refer to it.
[src:misra-c/misra-c] Each Guideline is classified as *Mandatory* (new for MISRA C:2012), *Required* or *Advisory*.
[src:misra-c/misra-c] Furthermore, the MISRA Compliance document permits *Advisory* guidelines to be *Disapplied*.
[src:misra-c/misra-c] MISRA C:2012 separately classifies each guideline as either *Single Translation Unit* or *System*.
[src:misra-c/misra-c] MISRA C:2012 classifies the *rules* (but not the *directives*) as *Decidable* or *Undecidable*.
[src:misra-c/misra-c] MISRA published documents to provide additional guidance to understand and achieve MISRA compliance.
[src:misra-c/misra-c] In order for a piece of software to claim to be compliant to the MISRA C Guidelines, all *mandatory* rules shall be met and all *required* rules and directives shall either be met or subject to a formal deviation.
[src:misra-c/misra-c] *Advisory* rules may be disapplied without a formal deviation, but this should still be recorded in the project documentation.
[src:misra-c/misra-c] Note: For compliance purposes, there is no distinction between *rules* and *directives*.
[src:misra-c/misra-c] Many MISRA C *rules* can be characterized as *guidelines* because under certain condition software engineers may deviate from rules and still be considered compliant with the standard.
[src:misra-c/misra-c] Deviations must be documented either in the code or in a file.
[src:misra-c/misra-c] The first edition of MISRA C, "Guidelines for the use of the C language in vehicle based software", which was published in 1998 and is officially known as *MISRA-C:1998*.
[src:misra-c/misra-c] MISRA-C:1998 has 127 rules, of which 93 are required and 34 are advisory; the rules are numbered in sequence from 1 to 127.
[src:misra-c/misra-c] In 2004, a second edition "Guidelines for the use of the C language in ***critical systems***", or *MISRA-C:2004* was produced, with many substantial changes to the guidelines, including a complete renumbering of the rules.
[src:misra-c/misra-c] MISRA-C:2004 contains 142 rules, of which 122 are "required" and 20 are "advisory"; they are divided into 21 topical categories, from "Environment" to "Run-time failures".
[src:misra-c/misra-c] In 2013, the third edition, MISRA C:2012, was published.
[src:misra-c/misra-c] MISRA C:2012 extends support to the C99 version of the C language (while maintaining guidelines for C90), in addition to including a number of improvements that can reduce the cost and complexity of compliance, whilst aiding consistent, safe use of C in critical systems.
[src:misra-c/misra-c] MISRA-C:2012 contains 143 rules and 16 "directives" (that is, rules whose compliance is more open to interpretation, or relates to process or procedural matters); each of which is classified as *mandatory*, *required*, or *advisory*.
[src:misra-c/misra-c] They are separately classified as either *Single Translation Unit* or *System*.
[src:misra-c/misra-c] Additionally, the rules are classified as *Decidable* or *Undecidable*.
[src:misra-c/misra-c] In April 2016, MISRA published (as a free download) *MISRA C:2012 - Amendment 1: Additional Security Guidelines* which added fourteen new security guidelines.
[src:misra-c/misra-c] In February 2020, MISRA published (as a free download) *MISRA C:2012 - Amendment 2: Updates for ISO/IEC 9899:2011/18 Core functionality* which adds mapping for the undefined, unspecified and implementation defined behaviours within C11/C18.
[src:misra-c/misra-c] In May 2023 MISRA published MISRA C:2023 (MISRA C Third edition, Second revision) which incorporates Amendments 2 – 4 (AMD2, AMD3, AMD4) and Technical Corrigendum 2 (TC2) and incorporates support for C11 and C17 language features.
[src:misra-c/misra-c] In March 2025 MISRA published MISRA C:2025.
[src:misra-c/misra-c] An exemplar suite (for MISRA-C:2004 and MISRA C:2012) is available from the MISRA GitLab repository (login required).
[src:misra-c/misra-c] This allows tool-users to evaluate and compare the checking support provided by the various MISRA tools; additionally, it gives tool-implementers some guidance as to the intent of the MISRA Guidelines.
[src:misra-c/misra-c] While there exist many software tools that claim to check code for "MISRA conformance", there is no MISRA certification process.
[src:misra-c/misra-c] Most of the guidelines can be checked using tools that perform static code analysis.
[src:misra-c/misra-c] The remaining guidelines require the use of dynamic code analysis.
[src:misra-c/misra-c] Some research results question the effectiveness of MISRA C 2004.
[src:misra-c/misra-c] A study at the TU Delft, by Cathal Boogerd and Leon Moonen, empirically assesses the value of MISRA C:2004.
[src:misra-c/safety-critical-system] A **safety-related system** (or sometimes **safety-involved system**) comprises everything (hardware, software, and human aspects) needed to perform one or more safety functions, in which failure would cause a significant increase in the safety risk for the people or environment involved.
[src:misra-c/safety-critical-system] Safety-related systems are those that do not have full responsibility for controlling hazards such as loss of life, severe injury or severe environmental damage.
[src:misra-c/safety-critical-system] The malfunction of a safety-involved system would only be that hazardous in conjunction with the failure of other systems or human error.
[src:misra-c/safety-critical-system] Some safety organizations provide guidance on safety-related systems, for example the Health and Safety Executive in the United Kingdom.
[src:misra-c/safety-critical-system] Risks of this sort are usually managed with the methods and tools of safety engineering.
[src:misra-c/safety-critical-system] A safety-critical system is designed to lose less than one life per billion (109) hours of operation.
[src:misra-c/safety-critical-system] Typical design methods include probabilistic risk assessment, a method that combines failure mode and effects analysis (FMEA) with fault tree analysis.
[src:misra-c/safety-critical-system] Safety-critical systems are increasingly computer-based.
[src:misra-c/safety-critical-system] Safety-critical systems are a concept often used together with the Swiss cheese model to represent (usually in a bow-tie diagram) how a threat can escalate to a major accident through the failure of multiple critical barriers.
[src:misra-c/safety-critical-system] This use has become common especially in the domain of process safety, in particular when applied to oil and gas drilling and production both for illustrative purposes and to support other processes, such as asset integrity management and incident investigation.
[src:misra-c/safety-critical-system] Software engineering for safety-critical systems is particularly difficult.
[src:misra-c/safety-critical-system] There are three aspects which can be applied to aid the engineering software for life-critical systems.
[src:misra-c/safety-critical-system] First is process engineering and management.
[src:misra-c/safety-critical-system] Secondly, selecting the appropriate tools and environment for the system.
[src:misra-c/safety-critical-system] This allows the system developer to effectively test the system by emulation and observe its effectiveness.
[src:misra-c/safety-critical-system] Thirdly, address any legal and regulatory requirements, such as Federal Aviation Administration requirements for aviation.
[src:misra-c/safety-critical-system] By setting a standard for which a system is required to be developed under, it forces the designers to stick to the requirements.
[src:misra-c/safety-critical-system] The avionics industry has succeeded in producing standard methods for producing life-critical avionics software.
[src:misra-c/safety-critical-system] Similar standards exist for industry, in general, (IEC 61508) and automotive (ISO 26262), medical (IEC 62304) and nuclear (IEC 61513) industries specifically.
[src:misra-c/safety-critical-system] The standard approach is to carefully code, inspect, document, test, verify and analyze the system.
[src:misra-c/safety-critical-system] Another approach is to certify a production system, a compiler, and then generate the system's code from specifications.
[src:misra-c/safety-critical-system] Another approach uses formal methods to generate proofs that the code meets requirements.
[src:misra-c/safety-critical-system] All of these approaches improve the software quality in safety-critical systems by testing or eliminating manual steps in the development process, because people make mistakes, and these mistakes are the most common cause of potential life-threatening errors.
[src:misra-c/safety-critical-system] The technology requirements can go beyond avoidance of failure, and can even facilitate medical *intensive care* (which deals with healing patients), and also *life support* (which is for stabilizing patients).
[src:misra-c/software-bug] A **software bug** is a defect (bug) in computer software.
[src:misra-c/software-bug] A computer program with many or serious bugs may be described as *buggy*.
[src:misra-c/software-bug] The effects of a software bug range from minor (such as a misspelled word in the user interface) to severe (such as frequent crashing).
[src:misra-c/software-bug] Since the 1950s, some computer systems have been designed to detect or auto-correct various software errors during operations.
[src:misra-c/software-bug] The term *bug* to describe a defect has been engineering jargon since at least as far back as the 1870s, long before electronic computers and computer software.
[src:misra-c/software-bug] Problems with military gear during World War II were referred to as bugs or glitches.
[src:misra-c/software-bug] Isaac Asimov used the term *bug* to relate to issues with a robot in his short story "Catch That Rabbit," published in 1944.
[src:misra-c/software-bug] Grace Hopper, a computer pioneer, popularized a story about a moth that caused a problem in an early electromechanical computer.
[src:misra-c/software-bug] While Hopper was working on the Mark II and Mark III as Harvard faculty in about 1947, operators traced an error in the Mark II to a moth trapped in a relay.
[src:misra-c/software-bug] Even if a joke, the story indicates that the term was commonly used in the computer field at that time.
[src:misra-c/software-bug] Different stages of a mistake in the development cycle may be described as mistake,anomaly, fault, failure, error, exception, crash, glitch, bug, defect, incident, or side effect.
[src:misra-c/software-bug] Software bugs have been linked to disasters.
[src:misra-c/software-bug] Sometimes the use of *bug* to describe the behavior of software is contentious due to perception.
[src:misra-c/software-bug] Some suggest that the term should be abandoned, contending that *bug* implies that the defect arose on its own, and push to use *defect* instead, since it more clearly indicates they are caused by a human.
[src:misra-c/software-bug] Some contend that *bug* may be used to cover up an intentional design decision.
[src:misra-c/software-bug] In 2011, after receiving scrutiny from US Senator Al Franken for recording and storing users' locations in unencrypted files, Apple called the behavior a bug.
[src:misra-c/software-bug] Preventing bugs as early as possible in the software development process is a target of investment and innovation.
[src:misra-c/software-bug] Newer programming languages tend to be designed to prevent common bugs based on vulnerabilities of existing languages.
[src:misra-c/software-bug] Lessons learned from older languages such as BASIC and C are used to inform the design of later languages such as C# and Rust.
[src:misra-c/software-bug] A compiled language allows for detecting some typos (such as a misspelled identifier) before runtime which is earlier in the software development process than for an interpreted language.
[src:misra-c/software-bug] Languages may include features such as a static type system, restricted namespaces, and modular programming.
[src:misra-c/software-bug] is syntactically correct, but fails type checking since the right side, a string, cannot be assigned to a float variable.
[src:misra-c/software-bug] Compilation fails – forcing this defect to be fixed before development progress can resume.
[src:misra-c/software-bug] With an interpreted language, a failure would not occur until the statement was executed (much later, if ever, during runtime).
[src:misra-c/software-bug] Some languages exclude features that easily lead to bugs, at the expense of slower performance – the principle being that it is usually better to write simpler, slower correct code than complicated, buggy code.
[src:misra-c/software-bug] For example, Java does not support pointer arithmetic which can be very fast but may lead to memory corruption or segmentation faults if not used with great caution.
[src:misra-c/software-bug] Some languages include features that add runtime overhead in order to prevent common bugs.
[src:misra-c/software-bug] For example, many languages include runtime bounds checking and a way to recover from out-of-bounds errors instead of crashing.
[src:misra-c/software-bug] Style guidelines and defensive programming can prevent easy-to-miss typographical errors (typos).
[src:misra-c/software-bug] For example, most C-family programming languages allow the omission of braces around an instruction block if there's only a single instruction.
[src:misra-c/software-bug] Enforcement of conventions may be manual (i.e. via code review) or via automated tools such as linters.
[src:misra-c/software-bug] Some contend that writing a program specification, which states the intended behavior of a program, can prevent bugs.
[src:misra-c/software-bug] Others, however, contend that formal specifications are impractical for anything but the shortest programs, because of problems of combinatorial explosion and indeterminacy.
[src:misra-c/software-bug] One goal of software testing is to find bugs.
[src:misra-c/software-bug] Measurements during testing can provide an estimate of the number of likely bugs remaining.
[src:misra-c/software-bug] This becomes more reliable the longer a product is tested and developed.
[src:misra-c/software-bug] Agile software development may involve frequent software releases with relatively small changes.
[src:misra-c/software-bug] With test-driven development (TDD), unit tests are written while writing the production code, and the production code is not considered complete until all tests have been written and complete successfully.
[src:misra-c/software-bug] Tools for static code analysis help developers by inspecting the program text beyond the compiler's capabilities to spot potential problems.
[src:misra-c/software-bug] Although in general the problem of finding all programming errors given a specification is not solvable (see halting problem), these tools exploit the fact that human programmers tend to make certain kinds of simple mistakes when writing software.
[src:misra-c/software-bug] Tools to monitor the performance of the software as it is running, either specifically to find problems such as bottlenecks or to give assurance as to correct working, may be embedded in the code explicitly (perhaps as simple as a statement saying `PRINT "I AM HERE"`), or provided as tools.
[src:misra-c/software-bug] It is often a surprise to find that most of the time is taken by a piece of code, and this removal of assumptions might cause the code to be rewritten.
[src:misra-c/software-bug] Open source development allows anyone to examine source code.
[src:misra-c/software-bug] A school of thought popularized by Eric S.
[src:misra-c/software-bug] Raymond as Linus's law says that popular open-source software has more chance of having few or no bugs than other software, because "given enough eyeballs, all bugs are shallow".
[src:misra-c/software-bug] Typically, the first step in locating a bug is to reproduce it reliably.
[src:misra-c/software-bug] If unable to reproduce the issue, a programmer cannot find the cause of the bug and therefore cannot fix it.
[src:misra-c/software-bug] Some bugs are revealed by inputs that may be difficult to reproduce.
[src:misra-c/software-bug] Other bugs may stop occurring whenever the setup is augmented to help find the bug, such as running the program with a debugger; these are called *heisenbugs* (humorously named after the Heisenberg uncertainty principle).
[src:misra-c/software-bug] Sometimes, a bug is not an isolated flaw, but represents an error of thinking or planning on the part of the programmers.
[src:misra-c/software-bug] Often, such a *logic error* requires a section of the program to be overhauled or rewritten. a process known as code refactoring.
[src:misra-c/software-bug] A code review, stepping through the code, and imagining or transcribing the execution process, may often find errors without ever reproducing the bug as such.
[src:misra-c/software-bug] A program known as a debugger can help a programmer find faulty code by examining the inner workings of a program, such as executing code line-by-line and viewing variable values.
[src:misra-c/software-bug] As an alternative to using a debugger, code may be instrumented with logic to output debug information to trace program execution and view values.
[src:misra-c/software-bug] Output is typically to console, window, log file, or a hardware output, potentially driving an indicator LED.
[src:misra-c/software-bug] Since the 1990s, particularly following the Ariane 5 Flight 501 disaster, interest in automated aids to debugging rose, such as static code analysis by abstract interpretation.
[src:misra-c/software-bug] In an embedded system, the software is often modified to work around a hardware bug since software modifications can be cheaper and less disruptive than modifying the hardware.
[src:misra-c/software-bug] Bugs are managed via activities like documenting, categorizing, assigning, reproducing, correcting, and releasing the corrected code.
[src:misra-c/software-bug] Tools are often used to track bugs and other issues with software.
[src:misra-c/software-bug] Typically, different tools are used by the software development team to track their workload than by customer service to track user feedback.
[src:misra-c/software-bug] A tracked item is often called *bug*, *defect*, *ticket*, *issue*, *feature*, or for agile software development, *story*, or *epic*.
[src:misra-c/software-bug] Items are often categorized by aspects such as severity, priority, and version number(s) affected.
[src:misra-c/software-bug] In a process sometimes called triage, choices are made for each bug about whether and when to fix it based on information such as the bug's severity and priority and external factors such as development schedules.
[src:misra-c/software-bug] Triage generally does not include an investigation into the cause.
[src:misra-c/software-bug] Triage may occur regularly and minimally consists of reviewing new bugs since the previous triage, possibly extending to all open bugs.
[src:misra-c/software-bug] Attendees may include the project manager, the development manager, the test manager, the build manager, and technical experts.
[src:misra-c/software-bug] A bug severe enough to delay the release of the product is called a *show stopper*.
[src:misra-c/software-bug] Priority may be a combination of the bug's severity and the level of effort to fix.
[src:misra-c/software-bug] A bug with low severity but easy to fix may get a higher priority than a bug with moderate severity that requires significantly more effort to fix.
[src:misra-c/software-bug] A bug of sufficiently high priority may warrant a special release to fix it.
[src:misra-c/software-bug] Such a release is sometimes called a *patch*.
[src:misra-c/software-bug] A software release that emphasizes bug fixes may be called a *maintenance* release – to differentiate it from a release that emphasizes new features or other changes.
[src:misra-c/software-bug] It is common practice to release software with known, low-priority bugs or other issues.
[src:misra-c/software-bug] The amount and type of damage a software bug may cause affects decision-making, processes, and policy regarding software quality.
[src:misra-c/software-bug] In applications such as banking, where software flaws have the potential to cause serious financial damage to a bank or its customers, quality control is also more important than, say, a photo editing application.
[src:misra-c/software-bug] Other than the damage caused by bugs, some of their cost is due to the effort invested in fixing them.
[src:misra-c/software-bug] In 1978, Lientz et al. showed that the median of projects invest 17 percent of their development effort in bug fixing.
[src:misra-c/software-bug] In 2020, research on GitHub repositories showed the median is 20 percent.
[src:misra-c/software-bug] In 1994, NASA's Goddard Space Flight Center managed to reduce their average number of errors from 4.5 per 1,000 lines of code (SLOC) to 1 per 1000 SLOC.
[src:misra-c/software-bug] Another study in 1990 reported that exceptionally good software development processes can achieve deployment failure rates as low as 0.1 per 1000 SLOC.
[src:misra-c/software-bug] This figure is iterated in literature such as *Code Complete* by Steve McConnell, and the *NASA study on Flight Software Complexity*.
[src:misra-c/software-bug] Some projects even attained zero defects: the firmware in the IBM Wheelwriter typewriter which consists of 63,000 SLOC, and the Space Shuttle software with 500,000 SLOC.
[src:misra-c/software-bug] A bug can be caused by insufficient or incorrect design based on the specification.
[src:misra-c/software-bug] For example, given that the specification is to alphabetize a list of words, a design bug might occur if the design does not account for symbols, resulting in incorrect alphabetization of words with symbols.
[src:misra-c/software-bug] Numerical operations can result in unexpected output, slow processing, or crashing.
[src:misra-c/software-bug] A control flow bug, or logic error, is characterized by code that does not fail with an error, but does not have the expected behavior, such as infinite looping, infinite recursion, incorrect comparison in a conditional such as using the wrong comparison operator, and the off-by-one error.
[src:misra-c/software-bug] The Open Technology Institute, run by the group, New America, released a report "Bugs in the System" in August 2016 stating that U.S. policymakers should make reforms to help researchers identify and address software bugs.
[src:misra-c/software-bug] Government researchers, companies, and cyber security experts are the people who typically discover software flaws.
[src:misra-c/software-bug] The report calls for reforming computer crime and copyright laws.
[src:misra-c/static-program-analysis] The term is usually applied to analysis performed by an automated tool, with human analysis typically being called "program understanding", program comprehension, or code review.
[src:misra-c/static-program-analysis] In the last of these, software inspection and software walkthroughs are also used.
[src:misra-c/static-program-analysis] In most cases the analysis is performed on some version of a program's source code, and, in other cases, on some form of its object code.
[src:misra-c/static-program-analysis] The discipline of static analysis should not be confused with linting, which is the process of checking for coding style mistakes.
[src:misra-c/static-program-analysis] The sophistication of the analysis performed by tools varies from those that only consider the behaviour of individual statements and declarations, to those that include the complete source code of a program in their analysis.
[src:misra-c/static-program-analysis] The uses of the information obtained from the analysis vary from highlighting possible coding errors (e.g., the lint tool) to formal methods that mathematically prove properties about a given program (e.g., its behaviour matches that of its specification).
[src:misra-c/static-program-analysis] Software metrics and reverse engineering can be described as forms of static analysis.
[src:misra-c/static-program-analysis] Deriving software metrics and static analysis are increasingly deployed together, especially in creation of embedded systems, by defining so-called *software quality objectives*.
[src:misra-c/static-program-analysis] A growing commercial use of static analysis is in the verification of properties of software used in safety-critical computer systems and locating potentially vulnerable code.
[src:misra-c/static-program-analysis] Nuclear software: In the UK the Office for Nuclear Regulation (ONR) recommends the use of static analysis on reactor protection systems.
[src:misra-c/static-program-analysis] Aviation software (in combination with dynamic analysis).
[src:misra-c/static-program-analysis] Automotive & Machines (functional safety features form an integral part of each automotive product development phase, ISO 26262, section 8).
[src:misra-c/static-program-analysis] A study in 2012 by VDC Research reported that 28.7% of the embedded software engineers surveyed use static analysis tools and 39.7% expect to use them within 2 years.
[src:misra-c/static-program-analysis] A study from 2010 found that 60% of the interviewed developers in European research projects made at least use of their basic IDE built-in static analyzers.
[src:misra-c/static-program-analysis] However, only about 10% employed an additional other (and perhaps more advanced) analysis tool.
[src:misra-c/static-program-analysis] In the application security industry the name static application security testing (SAST) is also used.
[src:misra-c/static-program-analysis] SAST is an important part of Security Development Lifecycles (SDLs) such as the SDL defined by Microsoft and a common practice in software companies.
[src:misra-c/static-program-analysis] The OMG (Object Management Group) published a study regarding the types of software analysis required for software quality measurement and assessment.
[src:misra-c/static-program-analysis] This document on "How to Deliver Resilient, Secure, Efficient, and Easily Changed IT Systems in Line with CISQ Recommendations" describes three levels of software analysis.
[src:misra-c/static-program-analysis] Analysis that takes place within a specific program or subroutine, without connecting to the context of that program.
[src:misra-c/static-program-analysis] Analysis that takes into account the interactions between unit programs, but without being limited to one specific technology or programming language.
[src:misra-c/static-program-analysis] A further level of software analysis can be defined.
[src:misra-c/static-program-analysis] Analysis that takes into account the business/mission layer terms, rules and processes that are implemented within the software system for its operation as part of enterprise or program/mission layer activities.
[src:misra-c/static-program-analysis] These elements are implemented without being limited to one specific technology or programming language and in many cases are distributed across multiple languages, but are statically extracted and analyzed for system understanding for mission assurance.
[src:misra-c/static-program-analysis] Many static analysis tools use intermediate representations of programs to examine the structure of source code without executing the program.
[src:misra-c/static-program-analysis] For this purpose, abstract syntax trees (ASTs) are commonly used, since they provide a structured representation of a program's syntactic elements.
[src:misra-c/static-program-analysis] Formal methods is the term applied to the analysis of software (and computer hardware) whose results are obtained purely through the use of rigorous mathematical methods.
[src:misra-c/static-program-analysis] The mathematical techniques used include denotational semantics, axiomatic semantics, operational semantics, and abstract interpretation.
[src:misra-c/static-program-analysis] This result dates from the works of Church, Gödel and Turing in the 1930s (see: Halting problem and Rice's theorem).
[src:misra-c/static-program-analysis] As with many undecidable questions, one can still attempt to give useful approximate solutions.
[src:misra-c/static-program-analysis] Data-driven static analysis leverages extensive codebases to infer coding rules and improve the accuracy of the analysis.
[src:misra-c/static-program-analysis] For instance, one can use all Java open-source packages available on GitHub to learn good analysis strategies.
[src:misra-c/static-program-analysis] The rule inference can use machine learning techniques.
[src:misra-c/static-program-analysis] It is also possible to learn from a large amount of past fixes and warnings.
[src:misra-c/static-program-analysis] For certain types of warnings, it is possible to design and implement automated remediation techniques.
[src:misra-c/static-program-analysis] For example, Logozzo and Ball have proposed automated remediations for C# *cccheck*.
